article.description: Sophomore forward Maya Moore scored 19 points to lead No. 1 Connecticut to an 85-40 victory over Northern Colorado on Friday night in the Caribbean Classic.
article.headline: No. 1 Huskies trail early, but not for long as Moore scores 19 to sink Bears
article.linkText: Moore steps up to pace No. 1 UConn in rout
article.story:
CANCUN, Mexico --  Faced with the unenviable task of facing top-ranked Connecticut, Northern Colorado coach Jaime White relied on a battled-tested methodology to motivate her team.

"We talked about how they are the same age as you are," White said. "You know, they have MySpace pages just like you do. Still, I think they were excited about playing one of the best teams we'll see, one of the best teams I've seen in all my years in basketball."

Sophomore forward Maya Moore scored 19 points to lead the top-ranked Huskies to an 85-40 rout of the smaller Bears on Friday night in the Caribbean Classic.

"She's pretty consistent with the way she plays," UConn coach Geno Auriemma said of Moore, a first-team All-American. "She plays at a very high level."

Renee Montgomery added 15 points for the Huskies (9-0), who wiped out a first-half deficit with a 14-2 run that put the game in their control. Each of UConn's 10 players scored, and junior center Kaili McLaren had eight points and a season-high 10 rebounds.

Senior guard Jamie Schroder led the Bears (4-6) with 17 points. Whitley Cox added 10, all in the first half.

The Huskies have a day before wrapping up the tournament Sunday against Florida State.

Northern Colorado, a member of the Big Sky Conference for just three seasons, made only 12 field goals overall and shot 3-for-33 in the second half of a 43-point loss to the Seminoles on Thursday. Still, the Bears led 7-6 in the opening minutes before UConn took control.

"Coach wanted us to limit the amount of shots they took, not so much the amount they made," Montgomery said. "The goal was not to let them do what they may have wanted to do."

Tina Charles, who had scored 29 points in each of her last two games, took a back seat to her All-American teammate in this one. Moore scored 15 points in the first half, helping the Huskies push the lead to 49-23 by halftime.

Charles wound up with just nine points -- she had only two at halftime -- after making all nine of hers hots in the first half Thursday.

Moore made her first five shots, including three three-pointers, and scored 13 of UConn's first 25 points. She added five rebounds, three assists and three steals.

She's on pace to score her 1,000th career point (she has 852 in 47 games) faster than any player in school history.

"I really don't think about those things," Moore said. "But scoring points for my team is something I do value."
